# Finding 07 — Plaintext Password Storage

**Severity:** Critical
**OWASP:** A02 Cryptographic Failures
**Status:** Verified fixed

## Description
User passwords were stored in plaintext in the database and compared directly against submitted values during login. No hashing or salting was applied. This was confirmed both through code review and through the unauthenticated user endpoint (Finding 03), which returned plaintext passwords for every account.

## Proof of Concept (sanitised)
Login comparison logic performed a direct string match:
```
if (user && user.password === submittedPassword) { ... }
```
Stored values were readable plaintext rather than hashes.

## Impact
Any database exposure would instantly compromise every user credential with no additional effort. Users reusing passwords elsewhere would be at risk on other platforms. Storing credentials in plaintext also runs contrary to data-protection expectations for personal data.

## Remediation
- Hash all passwords using bcrypt with an appropriate work factor
- Verify logins using a constant-time hash comparison
- Never store or return plaintext passwords at any point

## Verification
The development team migrated existing passwords to hashed storage and updated the login flow to compare against the hash. Storage format was confirmed as hashed. Confirmed resolved.

